AB  - When learning about someone else's behaviors, people often spontaneously infer character traits and ascribe them to the actor. The present study asks whether instructions to forget the behaviors immediately after they were encountered reduce spontaneous trait inferences (STIs). Participants encoded faces paired with trait-implying behavioral descriptions. Half of the pairs were followed by a forget and half by a remember cue. During test, faces were presented again, and participants were asked to recall the behavior and to indicate whether a specific trait word had been part of the original behavior description. Instructions to forget behaviors did not reduce false recognition of inferred traits but impaired behavior recall unless behavior memory was tested immediately after trait recognition for each face. Experiments 2 and 3 ensured that traits were bound to specific actors during encoding. Our study demonstrates that although trait-implying behaviors can be intentionally forgotten, spontaneously inferred traits prevail in memory.
   General Audience Summary When learning about someone else's behaviors, people often unknowingly and unintentionally infer character traits and ascribe them to the actor. The present study asks whether instructions to forget the behaviors reduce these spontaneous trait inferences. Participants saw faces paired with behavioral descriptions that implied a trait and were instructed to remember some of the face-behavior pairs for a later memory test, and to forget others because they would not be tested later. In a subsequent memory test including all face-behavior pairs, participants had difficulties recalling the forget-cued behaviors. Forgetting of behaviors, however, did not lead to forgetting of inferred traits. That is, spontaneously inferred traits (e.g., a person being "rude") prevailed in memory even when one was unable to recall the original source of these traits (e.g., the behavior that was interpreted as rude). Showing the robustness of memories for inferred traits-a core component of impressions-the present study provides a potential explanation for why first impressions are difficult to change. These findings also raise the possibility that biases in impressions (e.g., stereotypes, prejudice) are fostered by biases in memory, and specifically, the inability to update a memory related to a spontaneously inferred trait when being told to do so. Future research should investigate how people can effectively forget invalid information about others and explore whether forgetting can help people reduce their biases in real-world interactions.
